  <subsubsection|Mehool Patel, <em|Changes to Postgraduate Medical Education
  in the 21st Century>, 2016>

  <\description>
    <item*|Perspective>Changes of postgraduate medical training in the UK.

    <item*|Points>

    <\description>
      <item*|Structure>More standardised, structured, time-limited and
      consistent. Two reports:

      <\enumerate-numeric>
        <item>The Calman report. Mandatory defined end-point of training (7
        years). ensuring a doctor was required to have a postgraduate
        qualification in their chosen specialty before being on the register.

        <item>The Donaldson report. Aim: define a time-limited well-defined
        career pathway with defined educational goals; achieve a balance
        between service and training. encountered difficulties. the \Pgold
        guide\Q was first published in 2010.
      </enumerate-numeric>

      <item*|Commission>The Tooke report recommended the creation of MEE
      (Medical Education England), later HEE (Health Education England).
      Responsibilities: commissioning, delivering and improving training for
      all healthcare professionals in England, ensuring the workforce has the
      right numbers, skills, values and behaviour, at the right time and in
      the right place.

      <item*|Governance>Ensure that the quality of postgraduate training is
      regularly monitored in a consistent and transparent manner. Previous
      lacks: not responsive to change, \ not able to reflect consistent
      quality lacking transparency and responsiveness to patient care.
      Postgraduate Medical Education and Training Board (PMETB) was set up to
      address these problems.

      <item*|Impact of European Working Time Directive>Trainees are now
      exposed to training not only for fewer years but also for restricted
      hours (48 hours maximum). Consequently, there was reduced trainer and
      trainee interaction, reduced opportunity for continuity of patient
      care. But the Temple report states that high quality training can be
      delivered.
    </description>
  </description>

