  <\subsubsection>
    Lorne A. Chapnick, <em|Clinical Undergraduate Teaching>, 1999
  </subsubsection>

  <\description>
    <item*|Perspective>Dental schools in America.

    <item*|Points>

    <\description>
      <item*|Importance>

      Instructors can greatly influence student's learning process.

      <item*|Problems>

      Many endodontists were not qualified. They did not need to be trained
      or tested before teaching.

      Pure technical skill did not serve as adequate qualifications according
      to the 1988 World Conference on Medical Education.

      Some educators insists that abrasive personalities were not a problem.

      <item*|Expectations>

      Mostly the same as all teachers. \PHow can we help you\Q attitude; set
      goals and objectives; well order the learning materials; appropriate
      emotional tones to gain trust; eye contact & body language; create a
      relaxing environment; facilitation; help students activate knowledge;
      positive role model.

      <item*|Proposal>

      Clinical instructors should be receiving pedagogical training that
      emphasizes the significant impact on their students' pending careers.

      Demonstrate tangible ways through which instructors may improve their
      own personal performances.

      The role of dental educators should be formally defined to include the
      instructor's role as facilitator and role model.
    </description>
  </description>
